No seriously, the CMF Phone 1 delivers some amazing features and specs for it‚Äôs low price of $199. Here‚Äôs a breakdown of my experience:

Performance - Fluid, fast, kept up with everything I was doing. It‚Äôs no supercomputer, but it‚Äôs even decent at light gaming. I didn‚Äôt expect it to keep up this well.

Design - Where it really shines. Premium feel, IP52 rating, 120hz AMOLED display, modular with customizable accessories.

Features - The 50mp rear camera and 16mp front camera aren‚Äôt winning any awards, but they hold their own well. In screen optical fingerprint reader is a really nice touch.

Software - Nothing OS truly shines. It‚Äôs about as close to barebones Android as you can get other than a Pixel, but with Nothing‚Äôs special touches like Cloneable apps and their beautiful widgets and icons.

The bad?

Well, the speaker isn‚Äôt great. NFC is non-existent for you digital wallet lovers, and it‚Äôs really only good for T-Mobile in the US.

Still, at $199‚Ä¶ This is quite the impressive device, and it‚Äôs only version 1.

If you want to pick one up for yourself, you can check the Nothing website or get one on Amazon for a small premium. I‚Äôll have the link in my bio.
